President Donald J. Trump signed a proclamation declaring February 2017 as National African American History Month. The proclamation recognizes the heritage and achievements of African Americans and highlights their contributions to society. It mentions notable figures such as Katherine Johnson, Madam C.J. Walker, and Robert Smalls who broke barriers and made significant advancements in their respective fields. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of education and calls for ensuring that all children have access to quality educational opportunities. It also encourages meaningful dialogue, shared commitment, and collective action to uplift and empower African Americans. The proclamation concludes by calling upon public officials, educators, librarians, and all Americans to observe the month with appropriate programs, ceremonies, and activities.